 Objective: I have disabled ACLs in this setup so no intentions required. So the primary aim of this setup is to configure the Network Policies required for Consul
 service mesh communication to be established. There are scenarios where customer's namespaces are default set to deny for any ingress/egress communication. In such cases there is need to explicitly set the network policies for Consul service mesh communication.

Setup: Consul servers running on VM (my laptop)
       Applications (In Service mesh) deployed on Kubernetes cluster (kind cluster) with externalServers: field set to refer consul server.
       consul dataplane running on namespace consul-dp
       static-client running on app-ns1 namespace
       static-server running on app-ns2 namespace
       static-client in app-ns1 ns will be talking to static-server in app-ns2 ns.
Note: If you want to test Network policy in Kind cluster, you have to use some other cni and not the Kind default CNI (kindnet). Here I have used Calico CNI.

Steps:
1. Deploy kind cluster:
kind create cluster --config kind.yaml
Note: Make sure the pods subnet defined in kind.yaml does not have overlapping ip address as that of the Consul server running on VM. Else there will be connectivity issue.

2. Install the Calico CNI:
First, install the operator as usual:
kubectl create -f https://raw.githubusercontent.com/projectcalico/calico/v3.27.0/manifests/tigera-operator.yaml
Crucial Step: Do not apply the custom-resources.yaml directly from the internet URL. We need to modify it first so it matches our new Kind subnet.
Run this command to download it:
curl -O https://raw.githubusercontent.com/projectcalico/calico/v3.27.0/manifests/custom-resources.yaml
Open that downloaded custom-resources.yaml file in a text editor. Look for the cidr: line under ipPools and change it to 10.244.0.0/16 as defined in kind.yaml.
Apply the modified file:
kubectl create -f custom-resources.yaml

3. Verify the Installation
watch kubectl get pods -n calico-system

4. Deploy Consul server on VM (laptop-Mac)
nohup consul agent -config-file=consul.hcl &

5. Deploy Consul dataplane on Kubernetes:-
kubectl create ns consul-dp
secret=$(cat license.hclic)
kubectl create secret generic consul-ent-license -n consul-dp --from-literal="key=${secret}"
In another terminal run below command to expose Kubernetes api server url:
kubectl proxy --address='0.0.0.0' --port=8001 --accept-hosts='.*'
helm install consul hashicorp/consul -n consul-dp --values=values.yaml --debug

6. Deploy applications :-
kubectl create ns app-ns1
kubectl create ns app-ns2
kubectl apply -f static-client.yaml -n app-ns1
kubectl apply -f static-server.yaml -n app-ns2
kubectl apply -f static-client_wUpstream.yaml -n app-ns1 # With consul.hashicorp.com/connect-service-upstreams: annotation

7. Configure default deny and DNS allow network policies in app-ns1 and app-ns2 namespaces. When you apply a "Default Deny", it blocks absolutely everything—including DNS lookups. If your pods cannot reach kube-dns, they cannot resolve host.docker.internal or service names. You must apply both the Deny and the DNS Allow to both namespaces.
kubectl apply -f defaultdenyandDNSallow-app-ns1.yaml
kubectl apply -f defaultdenyandDNSallow-app-ns2.yaml
Exec into static-client app to connect to static-server, and you won't be able to connect it.
kubectl exec -it static-client-upstream-7fffc8849-qlhxz -c static-client-upstream -n app-ns1 -- sh
 # curl static-server.virtual.app-ns2.ns.consul

8. Now configure Control plane egress Network policy for namespaces consul-dp, app-ns1 and app-ns2.
kubectl apply -f allow-egress-to-mac-consul-app-ns1.yaml
kubectl apply -f allow-egress-to-mac-consul-app-ns2.yaml
kubectl apply -f allow-egress-to-mac-consul-consul-dp.yaml

9. Now configure Consul dataplane applications cross namespaces network policy. In my case I'll be creating egress NetPol for app-ns1 ns and ingress NetPol for app-ns2 ns.
kubectl apply -f egresspolicyforapp-ns1.yaml
kubectl apply -f ingresspolicyforapp-ns2.yaml

10. Validate:
Exec into static-client app to connect to static-server. 
abhineet@abhineet-M17KGYKQHL dbs % kubectl exec -it static-client-74bc477bcd-2rc4t -c static-client -n app-ns1 -- sh
/ # curl localhost:19000/listeners
outbound_listener:127.0.0.1:15001::127.0.0.1:15001
public_listener:10.244.82.13:20000::10.244.82.13:20000
/ # curl static-server.virtual.app-ns2.ns.consul
"hello world from dc1"
/ # curl localhost:1234
curl: (7) Failed to connect to localhost port 1234: Connection refused
/ #

Output from static-client-upstream pod: (With consul.hashicorp.com/connect-service-upstreams: annotation)
abhineet@abhineet-M17KGYKQHL dbs % kubectl exec -it static-client-upstream-7fffc8849-qlhxz -c static-client-upstream -n app-ns1 -- sh
/ # curl static-server.virtual.app-ns2.ns.consul
"hello world from dc1"
/ # curl localhost:1234
"hello world from dc1"
/ # curl localhost:19000/listeners
public_listener:10.244.82.18:20000::10.244.82.18:20000
default/app-ns2/static-server?dc=dc1:127.0.0.1:1234::127.0.0.1:1234
outbound_listener:127.0.0.1:15001::127.0.0.1:15001

Very Important Observation: If you see output from static-client-upstream pod, you get the ouput from both the ways i.e using "curl localhost:1234" and using "curl static-server.virtual.app-ns2.ns.consul"
But if you see output from static-client pod where no upstream annotation defined, you get output only for "curl static-server.virtual.app-ns2.ns.consul"


